    {
      "id": "22432cada919df3086dccdca2b7a143c510ff135",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-08-19 13:27:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI see what happen. With sysfs the name of the sysfs file created is based on the name of the function. In the original proc code the function name was different than the actual proc file but it didn't matter.\n\nThis was introduced right at the start of the development cycle of 2.13. We can easily change the sysfs file name.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "54256eb0f5a03c972ee096574508094827ae65e5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-08-19 13:34:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThis bug is only present for 2.13. We can change the name of the sysfs file to what it should be instead. This is user facing so we should avoid changing it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
